Statistical Programming in R

  1. Carry out a principal components analysis on the possum data for the following scenarios and compare the loadings for the first and second principal components in these new analyses.
  • all possums
  • only the female possums
  • only the male possums

Let us do the PCA for females,

require(DAAG)
## Loading required package: DAAG
## Loading required package: lattice
females <- princomp(na.omit(possum[possum$sex=="f", -(1:5)]))

for males,

males <- princomp(na.omit(possum[possum$sex=="m", -(1:5)]))

and for everyone.

everyone <- princomp(na.omit(possum[, -(1:5)]))

Now we extract the loadings,

fem<-females$loadings[,c("Comp.1", "Comp.2")]
mal<-males$loadings[,c("Comp.1", "Comp.2")]
all<-everyone$loadings[,c("Comp.1", "Comp.2")]

plot them,

plot(fem, ylim = c(-1,1), xlim=c(-1,1), col = "blue")
points(mal, col = "red")
points(all, col = "green")
abline(h = 0, col = "grey")
abline(v = 0, col = "grey")

and, finally, print them.

cbind(fem, mal, all)
##               Comp.1      Comp.2      Comp.1      Comp.2     Comp.1

It is clear that the combined data loads differently than the seperate parts. However, if we reverse the sign of the loadings for males and females we obtain a solution that is very similar to the solution for the combined data. Moreover we then see that males and females load quite opposite from one another on Component 2.

plot(fem * -1, ylim = c(-1,1), xlim=c(-1,1), col = "blue")
points(mal * -1, col = "red")
points(all, col = "green")
abline(h = 0, col = "grey")
abline(v = 0, col = "grey")

  1. Use the funtion PCA on the Decathlon dataset from FactoMineR to perform a principal components analysis.
require(FactoMineR)

pca <- PCA(decathlon[,1:10], scale.unit=TRUE, ncp=5, graph=T)

The first two Components account for about 50% of the variation in the variables. Based on the Eigenvalue criterion we select a 4 Components solution.

load <- sweep(pca$var$coord,2,sqrt(pca$eig[1:ncol(pca$var$coord),1]),FUN="/")
